{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b20e728f-c856-4975-ad2e-96a9e60eafae","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Event flow (typical):**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| Sent to background | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n| iOS backgrounding | `Backgrounding` (with state payload) |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is iOS-specific and provides a `BackgroundingEventArgs.State` dictionary you can use to persist transient data.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"141abb71-00ab-426b-b443-016553244a2d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about Window lifecycle events in .NET MAUI and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer it directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":438,"requestId":"500F:955C8:1BEBC79:1EF2067:69FA9082"},"id":"06bae74d-4fce-4850-870c-bdb09dec5194","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:51:22.806Z","parentId":"62674861-df97-455a-b7b7-beb5998a807b"}
